        optionFeedback: [`<!--Answers:-->Prostaglandins produced in the gastric epithelium promote numerous protective mechanisms, including suppression of acid secretion, increased production of mucins, and increased blood flow and epithelial restitution after injury. NSAIDs inhibit prostaglandin production, which suppresses inflammation systemically (prostaglandins are important mediators of inflammation). Individuals treated chronically with NSAIDs develop gastritis with acute ulcers because of the loss of mucosal defenses. `,`H. pylori infection is a cause of gastritis and ulcers but is unrelated to NSAID use.`,`Bicarbonate counteracts the effects of gastric acid and is thus also protective of the gastric mucosa. NSAIDs inhibit, rather than increase, bicarbonate production.`,`Prostaglandins promote mucosal blood flow, so their inhibition by NSAIDs results in reduced blood flow.`,`Vagal nerve stimulation is implicated as a causative factor in gastric “stress ulcers” associated with intracranial injury.`],
