        q: `A 51-year-old woman has been feeling increasingly tired for the past 7 months. There are no remarkable findings on physical examination. Laboratory studies include hemoglobin, 9.5 g/dL (12.0–16.0 g/dL); hematocrit, 29.1% (36%–46%); mean corpuscular volume (MCV), 124 µm<sup>3</sup> (80–100 μm<sup>3</sup>); platelet count, 168,000/mm<sup>3</sup> (150,000–400,000/mm<sup>3</sup>) and WBC count, 4,350/mm<sup>3</sup> (4,500–11,000/mm<sup>3</sup>). Hypersegmented polymorphonuclear leukocytes (PMNs) are found on a peripheral blood smear. The serum gastrin is markedly increased. Antibodies directed against which of the following are most likely to be found in this patient?`,
