        optionFeedback: [`<!--Answers:-->The clinical presentation (insidious onset of fatigue, anemia, hypersegmented PMNs and increased MCV are characteristic of megaloblastic anemias caused by deficiency of vitamin B<sub>12</sub> or folic acid. Folate deficiency is usually of nutritional origin, whereas B<sub>12</sub> deficiency may be caused by gastric disease that results in diminished intrinsic factor production or ileal disease that prevents uptake of B<sub>12</sub> intrinsic factor complexes. The increased gastrin production suggests that the stomach is involved by a disorder that is decreasing acid secretion. Collectively, these features indicate destruction of gastric parietal epithelial cells, which are the major producers of intrinsic factor (required for absorption of vitamin B<sub>12</sub>, which is essential for hematopoiesis) and gastric acid. The cause of this parietal damage is most often an autoimmune response. Autoantibodies are produced against the epithelial cells, but these may be secondary to a T-cell mediated attack on parietal cells, which is believed to be the source of the tissue damage. `,`Antibodies against gliadin (a component of gluten from wheat and other grains) are seen in celiac disease.`,`Antibodies against  H.   pylori may be seen in infected patients but do not cause lesions. This infection is associated with gastritis and peptic ulcer disease. Chronic bleeding from peptic ulcers may cause iron deficiency anemia, but not megaloblastic anemia. `,`Gastric antral cells are the site of injury in H. pylori gastritis and peptic ulcer disease, but not the targets of antibody-mediated injury. `,`T. whipplei is the cause of Whipple disease, an intestinal bacterial infection associated with malabsorption and systemic manifestations such as arthritis and cardiac abnormalities. `],
