        optionFeedback: [`Acute gastritis is a mucosal inflammatory process associated with presence of neutrophils among epithelial cells or within mucosal glands. The surface epithelium is intact but there is foveolar cell hyperplasia. Acute gastritis is caused by disruption of protective mechanisms of gastric mucosa as may occur with ingestion of NSAIDs and in uremic patients.`,`Although this patient may have H. pylori gastritis associated with peptic ulcer disease, polyps are not typically seen in this setting, which is more commonly associated with loss of rugal folds when inflammation is severe.`,`<!--Answers:-->Fundic gland polyps are caused by chronic use of proton pump inhibitors, which inhibit production of gastric acid, leading to a compensatory increase in secretion of gastrin, which stimulates proliferation of oxyntic gland cells, the epithelial cells found in the gastric fundus. `,`Gastric lymphoma is also associated with H. pylori infection, but it usually presents as a tumor infiltrating the mucosa, not polypoid masses.`,`Gastric carcinoma is another lesion associated with chronic H. pylori infection. It presents as ulcerating masses and malignant glands infiltrating the stomach wall. `],
