        optionFeedback: [`<!--Answers:-->The clinical history is suggestive of a GI cancer, and the endoscopy and histology (sheets of mucin-filled cells infiltrating the gastric wall) are diagnostic for diffuse infiltrative gastric adenocarcinoma (formerly known as linitis plastica). This tumor is consistently associated with loss of expression of the adhesion molecule E-cadherin, which is due to acquired mutations in about half of sporadic cases and epigenetic downregulation in the remaining half. The loss of cellular adhesion enables the tumor to infiltrate tissues as single malignant cells. `,`Beta-catenin is mutated in the intestinal form of gastric adenocarcinoma. This protein is part of the Wnt signaling pathway, which is consistently hyperactive in this type of gastric tumor.`,`KIT encodes a tyrosine kinase; mutations in the gene leading to overactivity of the kinase are found in gastrointestinal stromal tumor and mast cell disease.`,`BCL6 is mutated in diffuse large cell B cell lymphoma.`,`Activating mutations of BRAF are found in numerous tumors, including melanoma and colon cancer, but not gastric cancers.`],
