        optionFeedback: [`Autoimmune gastritis is not associated with H. pylori infection and does not present as a focal lesion with lymphoid infiltrates.`,`Chronic gastritis may be caused by H. pylori infection. It usually presents with epigastric discomfort and not a focal infiltrate of lymphoid cells. The inflammatory infiltrate seen in chronic gastritis is a mixed population of neutrophils, lymphocytes and macrophages, not a monomorphous population of lymphocytes.`,`Diffuse large B cell lymphoma is an aggressive neoplasm that may arise in the stomach. These tumors are not associated with H. pylori infection.`,`Gastrointestinal stromal tumor (GIST) is a mesenchymal tumor arising in the musculature of the gastric wall, not the mucosa. It is not associated with H. pylori infection. `,`<!--Answers:-->Patients with H. pylori infection develop lymphomas that typically arise from marginal zone B cells. These extranodal marginal zone lymphoma are also known as mucosa-associated lymphoid tumor, or MALToma. The continued growth of this tumor is dependent on the infection, suggesting that the host response to the bacteria is involved in initiation and maintenance of the tumor.`],
