        optionFeedback: [`Antibiotics would not be helpful for this tumor. They may be beneficial for H. pylori-associated extranodal marginal zone lymphoma of the stomach.`,`Retinoic acid is used as differentiation therapy for one type of leukemia but would not have an effect on this tumor.`,`Anti-EGFR antibodies are efficacious in tumors associated with EGFR mutation or overexpression (some lung and breast cancers). The EGF receptor also is a tyrosine kinase, but it is not involved in GIST. `,`<!--Answers:-->The history is that of a gastric tumor; endoscopic biopsy is diagnostic for gastrointestinal stromal tumor (GIST), a tumor of mesenchymal cells that is strongly associated with mutations in the receptor tyrosine kinase KIT and, less commonly, PDGFRA (platelet-derived growth factor receptor α). KIT is a receptor for stem cell factor (also known as KIT ligand). The mutation results in constitutive signaling, leading to unregulated proliferation, and is responsive to tyrosine kinase inhibitor therapy. `,`Corticosteroids are antiinflammatory drugs that would not be beneficial for this or any other solid tumor. They are used to treat many lymphoid malignancies.`],
