        optionFeedback: [`Anticentromere antibodies are most often seen in systemic sclerosis.`,`Anti-DNA topoisomerase antibodies are most often seen in systemic sclerosis.`,`Antimitochondrial antibodies are seen in primary biliary cholangitis.`,`Antinuclear antibody is seen in lupus and other autoimmune diseases. `,`<!--Answers:-->The clinical presentation suggests a malabsorption syndrome. The histologic findings are suggestive of celiac disease. This could be proven by withdrawing and then challenging with gluten-containing food. Patients with the disease frequently make antibodies (often IgA) against tissue transglutaminase. The role of these antibodies in the pathogenesis of celiac disease is unclear; transglutaminase may be involved in chemical modification of gliadin, the major gluten-containing protein in wheat and other grains, and the modified protein may elicit damaging immune responses in some individuals. `],
