        q: `A 65-year-old woman is being treated in the hospital for pneumonia complicated by septicemia. She has required multiple antibiotics and was intubated and mechanically ventilated earlier in the course. On day 20 of hospitalization, she has abdominal distention. Bowel sounds are absent, and an abdominal radiograph shows dilated loops of small bowel suggestive of ileus. Laboratory studies show leukocytosis and hypoalbuminemia. At laparotomy, a portion of distal ileum and cecum is resected. The mucosal surface is covered by an irregular sheath of necrotic debris with enmeshed inflammatory cells. Which of the following is the most likely causative agent of these clinical and pathologic features?`,
