        q: `A study of children living in rural Malawi in Africa reveals a high prevalence of iron deficiency anemia. Stool samples are positive for occult blood. Pruritus of the skin of their feet as well as cough is an additional finding in many of these children. Which of the following parasitic infestations is the most likely cause for these findings?`,
        q2: ``,
        q3: [],
        option: [`Ancylostoma duodenale`,`Ascaris lumbricoides`,`Entamoeba histolytica`,`Giardia lamblia`,`Strongyloides stercoralis`],
        optionFeedback: [`<!--Answers:-->Necator americanus and Ancylostoma duodenale are hookworms that initiate infection by larval penetration through the skin. They develop in the lungs and are swallowed and complete their maturation in the duodenum. Here the adult worms attach to the mucosa, suck blood, and reproduce. Because of the chronic blood loss, hookworm infections are a leading cause of iron deficiency anemia in developing countries. `,`Ascaris lumbricoides is a nematode that infects individuals by fecal-oral transmission of the parasite’s eggs. In the intestine, the eggs hatch to release larvae, which penetrate the mucosa and migrate first to the liver, creating hepatic abscesses, and then to the lungs, where they cause pneumonia. There is no loss of blood.`,`Entamoeba histolytica causes amebic dysentery presenting with painful bloody diarrhea. Anemia is not the dominant feature.`,`Giardia lamblia, a flagellated protozoan, is the most common pathogenic parasite in humans. Infection is acquired by ingestion of cysts in contaminated food or water. Trophozoites are released in the acidic environment of the stomach and damage intestinal microvilli, causing apoptosis of epithelial cells. The infection may lead to acute or chronic malabsorptive diarrhea, but it is typically non-bloody. `,`Strongyloides stercoralis larvae live in fecally contaminated soil and can penetrate the skin. From here, they migrate to the lungs, are swallowed from the trachea, and mature into adult worms in the intestine. The eggs hatch in the intestine and release larvae that continue a cycle of autoinfection. The usual clinical presentation is intermittent gastrointestinal, pulmonary, or cutaneous symptoms that may continue for many years. `],
