        optionFeedback: [`Mutations in the APC gene are associated with familial adenomatous polyposis and colon adenocarcinoma, not Crohn disease.`,`<!--Answers:-->The clinical history suggests an inflammatory bowel disease. The presence of a fistula, the colonoscopic appearance of “skip” lesions, and the morphologic findings (especially crypt abscesses and granulomas) are diagnostic of Crohn disease. A subset of these patients has polymorphisms in the NOD2 gene. Although the presence of two mutant NOD2 alleles significantly increases the risk of developing the disease, identification of mutations is not of diagnostic or prognostic value, so genetic testing is not recommended. NOD2 is a cytosolic sensor of microbes, and triggers host reactions that combat microbes (a mechanism of innate immunity). It is postulated that the disease-associated polymorphisms encode a version of NOD2 that is not fully functional, allowing commensal bacteria to penetrate the intestinal wall and induce chronic inflammation. `,`HLA associations are seen with many autoimmune diseases, and HLA-DQ2 is associated with celiac disease, but Crohn disease and ulcerative colitis are not associated with any HLA allele.`,`Mutations in mismatch repair genes, which are often manifested as microsatellite instability, are associated with some forms of colonic adenoma and adenocarcinoma. The hereditary form of this disease is hereditary nonpolyposis colorectal carcinoma (HNPCC).`,`Microsatellite instability is associated with mutations in mismatch repair genes and predisposition to  colonic adenoma and adenocarcinoma. The hereditary form of this disease is hereditary nonpolyposis colorectal carcinoma (HNPCC). `],
